# Cline Rules for this Repository

## Session start behavior
- At the start of every task, read these files before planning or editing:
  - `memory-bank/projectbrief.md`
  - `memory-bank/productContext.md`
  - `memory-bank/systemPatterns.md`
  - `memory-bank/techContext.md`
  - `memory-bank/activeContext.md`
  - `memory-bank/progress.md`

## Memory-bank maintenance
- After any meaningful change, update `memory-bank/activeContext.md` and `memory-bank/progress.md`.
- If project goals/scope change, update `memory-bank/projectbrief.md`.
- If workflows or user expectations change, update `memory-bank/productContext.md`.
- If architecture/patterns change, update `memory-bank/systemPatterns.md`.
- If tools/platform/dependencies change, update `memory-bank/techContext.md`.

## Documentation quality rules
- Keep entries specific to this repo (no generic placeholders).
- Reference exact file paths when describing behavior.
- Prefer concise, factual updates over long narrative text.
- Preserve macOS-focused context and script idempotency assumptions.

# RTK - Rust Token Killer (Cline)

**Usage**: Token-optimized CLI proxy for shell commands.

## Rule

Always prefix shell commands with `rtk` to minimize token consumption.

Examples:

```bash
rtk git status
rtk cargo test
rtk ls src/
rtk grep "pattern" src/
rtk find "*.rs" .
rtk docker ps
rtk gh pr list
```

## Meta Commands

```bash
rtk gain              # Show token savings
rtk gain --history    # Command history with savings
rtk discover          # Find missed RTK opportunities
rtk proxy <cmd>       # Run raw (no filtering, for debugging)
```

## Why

RTK filters and compresses command output before it reaches the LLM context, saving 60-90% tokens on common operations. Always use `rtk <cmd>` instead of raw commands.
